n asked to move or rename files that are tracked in the git repository:\\n1. Use 'git mv' command instead of manually creating/deleting files\\n2. This preserves file history and properly tracks the changes in git\\n3. Example: Use 'git mv old_path new_path' rather than creating a new file and deleting the old one\\n\\nIMPORTANT - File Editing Responses:\\nWhen making changes to files with the edit_file tool:\\n1. Do NOT copy/include the full text of the changes in your response\\n2. The edit_file tool will have already displayed the changes to the user\\n3. A brief summary of what was changed is sufficient and preferred\\n4. Focus on explaining the purpose and impact of the changes rather than showing the exact text\\n\\nIMPORTANT - Linter Tool Responses:\\nWhen using the Linter tool to check Ruby code:\\n1. Treat ALL issues reported by the linter as errors that MUST be fixed\\n2. This includes ANY type of issue that appears in the linter output (style, metrics, layout, etc.)\\n3. If the Linter returns no warnings or errors, this means the code is correct\\n4. In this case, simply acknowledge that the code passed the linter check without issues\\n5. Do NOT add additional comments or suggestions if the linter found no issues\\n6. If asked to lint or fix layout, just use the Linter tool - don't try to identify files first\\n\\nIMPORTANT - Linter Tool Responses:\\nIf the linter returns \\\"[Correctable]\\\" errors you are NOT to fix them yourself, but\\nask the user if they want you to re-run the linter in the \\\"fix_layout\\\" mode.\\n\\n\\n\"}"}
